#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:86
msgid "Image data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:88
msgid ""
"The format for image data is detailed in the Figure 1 where the `Type` "
"attribute of the `VTKHDF` group is `ImageData`.  An ImageData (regular grid) "
"is not split into partitions for parallel processing. We rely on the writer "
"to chunk the data to optimize reading for a certain number of MPI ranks. "
"Attribute data is stored in a PointData or CellData array using hyper slabs. "
"`WholeExtent`, `Origin`, `Spacing` and `Direction` attributes have the same "
"meaning as the corresponding attributes for the vtkImageData dataset. "
"`Scalars`, `Vectors`, ... string attributes for the `PointData` and "
"`CellData` groups specify the active attributes in the dataset."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:132
msgid ""
"<div align=\"center\">\n"
"Figure 1. - Image Data VTKHDF File Format\n"
"</div>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:137
msgid "Unstructured grid"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:139
msgid ""
"The format for unstructured grid is shown in Figure 2. In this case the "
"`Type` attribute of the `VTKHDF` group is `UnstructuredGrid`. The "
"unstructured grid is split into partitions, with a partition for each MPI "
"rank. This is reflected in the HDF5 file structure. Each HDF dataset is "
"obtained by concatenating the data for each partition. The offset O(i) where "
"we store the data for partition i is computed using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:146
#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:282
msgid "O(i) = S(0) + ... + S(i-1), i > 1 with O(0) = 0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:148
msgid "where S(i) is the size of partition i."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:150
msgid ""
"We describe the split into partitions using HDF5 datasets "
"`NumberOfConnectivityIds`, `NumberOfPoints` and `NumberOfCells`. Let n be "
"the number of partitions which usually correspond to the number of the MPI "
"ranks. `NumberOfConnectivityIds` has size n where NumberOfConnectivityIds[i] "
"represents the size of the `Connectivity` array for partition i. "
"`NumberOfPoints` and `NumberOfCells` are arrays of size n, where "
"NumberOfPoints[i] and NumberOfCells[i] are the number of points and number "
"of cells for partition i. The `Points` array contains the points of the VTK "
"dataset. `Offsets` is an array of size ∑ (S(i) + 1), where S(i) is the "
"number of cells in partition i, indicating the index in the `Connectivity` "
"array where each cell's points start. `Connectivity` stores the lists of "
"point ids for each cell, and `Types` contain the cell information stored as "
"described in vtkCellArray documentation. Data for each partition is appended "
"in a HDF dataset for `Points`, `Connectivity`, `Offsets`, `Types`, "
"`PointData` and `CellData`. We can compute the size of partition i using the "
"following formulas:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "Size of partition i"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "Points"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "NumberOfPoints[i] * 3 * sizeof(Points[0][0])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
msgid "Connectivity"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
msgid "NumberOfConnectivityIds[i] * sizeof(Connectivity[0])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
msgid "Offsets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
msgid "(NumberOfCells[i] + 1) * sizeof(Offsets[0])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
msgid "Types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
msgid "NumberOfCells[i] * sizeof(Types[i])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "PointData"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "NumberOfPoints[i] * sizeof(point_array_k[0])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "CellData"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:99
msgid "NumberOfCells[i] * sizeof(cell_array_k[0])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:226
msgid ""
"<div align=\"center\">\n"
"Figure 2. - Unstructured Grid VTKHDF File Format\n"
"</div>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:230
#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:374
msgid ""
"To read the data for its rank a node reads the information about all "
"partitions, compute the correct offset and then read data from that offset."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:234
msgid "Polyhedron support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:236
msgid ""
"Unstructured grids can define polyhedron cells. In VTK, polyhedrons are "
"defined differently than other cells, using a collection of faces in "
"addition to vertices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:240
msgid ""
"VTKHDF uses new fields to handle polyhedral cells. These fields should be "
"defined as long as the dataset has one or more polyhedral cell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:243
msgid ""
"Faces are defined using a separate array of surfacic (2D) cells, using "
"offsets `FaceOffsets` and connectivity `FaceConnectivity` arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:246
msgid ""
"These faces are tied to 3D polyhedral cells using `PolyhedronToFaces` and "
"`PolyhedronOffsets`. `PolyhedronToFaces` gives the ids of the face cells "
"defined before, for each polyhedron. `PolyhedronOffsets` defines the read "
"offset into this array for each polyhedron, which also gives away the number "
"of faces for the current polyhedron by reading the very next value in the "
"array and substracting it to the current one. This means that a single "
"(oriented) face can be used by multiple polyhedrons."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:253
msgid ""
"When mixing polyhedral and non-polyhedral cells in the same dataset, the "
"value of `PolyhedronOffsets` should stay the same as the previous one when "
"the cell is non-polyhedral, and be incremented when the cell is a polyhedron "
"and defines faces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:257
msgid ""
"We also define new metadata fields: `NumberOfFaces`, "
"`NumberOfPolyhedronToFaceIds` and `NumberOfFaceConnectivityIds`. Those are "
"used for managing multiple partitions and/or time steps. These arrays have "
"one value for each partition/time step, and give the number of faces/face "
"connectivity ids/polyhedron to face ids to be read for the current part."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:261
msgid ""
"The table below summarizes the new non-metadata fields required for "
"polyhedral cells in VTKHDF, in addition to the ones used by the \"classic\" "
"Unstructured Grid model."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "FaceConnectivity"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "NumberOfFaceConnectivityIds[i] * sizeof(FaceConnectivity[i])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "FaceOffsets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "(NumberOfPolygonalFaces[i] + 1) * sizeof(FaceOffsets[i])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "PolyhedronToFaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "NumberOfPolyhedronToFaceIds[i] * sizeof(PolyhedronToFaces[0])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "PolyhedronOffsets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "(NumberOfCells[i] + 1) * sizeof(PolyhedronOffsets[0])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:273
msgid "Poly data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:275
msgid ""
"The format for poly data is shown in Figure 3. In this case the `Type` "
"attribute of the `VTKHDF` group is `PolyData`. The poly data is split into "
"partitions, with a partition for each MPI rank. This is reflected in the "
"HDF5 file structure. Each HDF dataset is obtained by concatenating the data "
"for each partition. The offset O(i) where we store the data for partition i "
"is computed using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:284
msgid ""
"where S(i) is the size of partition i. This is very similar to and "
"completely inspired by the `UnstructuredGrid` format."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:287
msgid ""
"The split into partitions of the point coordinates is exactly the same as in "
"the `UnstructuredGrid` format above. However, the split into partitions of "
"each of the category of cells (`Vertices`, `Lines`, `Polygons` and `Strips`) "
"using HDF5 datasets `NumberOfConnectivityIds` and `NumberOfCells`. Let n be "
"the number of partitions which usually correspond to the number of the MPI "
"ranks. `{CellCategory}/NumberOfConnectivityIds` has size n where "
"NumberOfConnectivityIds[i] represents the size of the `{CellCategory}/"
"Connectivity` array for partition i. `NumberOfPoints` and `{CellCategory}/"
"NumberOfCells` are arrays of size n, where NumberOfPoints[i] and "
"{CellCategory}/NumberOfCells[i] are the number of points and number of cells "
"for partition i. The `Points` array contains the points of the VTK dataset. "
"`{CellCategory}/Offsets` is an array of size ∑ (S(i) + 1), where S(i) is the "
"number of cells in partition i, indicating the index in the `{CellCategory}/"
"Connectivity` array where each cell's points start. `{CellCategory}/"
"Connectivity` stores the lists of point ids for each cell. Data for each "
"partition is appended in a HDF dataset for `Points`, `Connectivity`, "
"`Offsets`, `PointData` and `CellData`. We can compute the size of partition "
"i using the following formulas:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "{CellCategory}/Connectivity"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid ""
"{CellCategory}/NumberOfConnectivityIds[i] * sizeof({CellCategory}/"
"Connectivity[0])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "{CellCategory}/Offsets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid ""
"({CellCategory}/NumberOfCells[i] + 1) * sizeof({CellCategory}/Offsets[0])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:177
msgid "(∑j {CellCategory_j}/NumberOfCells[i]) * sizeof(cell_array_k[0])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:370
msgid ""
"<div align=\"center\">\n"
"Figure 3. - Poly Data VTKHDF File Format\n"
"</div>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:378
msgid "Overlapping AMR"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:380
msgid ""
"The format for Overlapping AMR is shown in Figure 4. In this case the `Type` "
"attribute of the `VTKHDF` group is `OverlappingAMR`. The mandatory `Origin` "
"parameter is a double triplet that defines the global origin of the AMR data "
"set. Each level in an overlapping AMR file format (and data structure) "
"consists of a list of uniform grids with the same spacing from the Spacing "
"attribute. The Spacing attribute is a list a three doubles describing the "
"spacing in each x/y/z direction. The AMRBox dataset contains the bounding "
"box for each of these grids. Each line in this dataset is expected to "
"contain 6 integers describing the indexed bounds in i, j, k space (imin/imax/"
"jmin/jmax/kmin/kmax). The points and cell arrays for these grids are stored "
"serialized in one dimension and stored in a dataset in the PointData or "
"CellData group."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:436
msgid ""
"<div align=\"center\">\n"
"Figure 4. Overlapping AMR VTKHDF File Format\n"
"</div>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:440
msgid "HyperTreeGrid"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:442
msgid ""
"The schema for the tree-based AMR HyperTreeGrid VTKHDF specification is "
"shown in Figure 5. This specification is very different from the ones "
"mentioned above, because its topology is defined as a grid of refined trees."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:445
msgid ""
"Root attribute `Dimensions` defines the dimension of the grid. For a `N * M "
"* P` grid, there are a total of `(N - 1) * (M - 1) * (P - 1)` trees. "
"Coordinates arrays `XCoordinates` (size `N`), `YCoordinates` (size `M`) and "
"`ZCoordinates` (size `P`) define the size of trees in each direction. Their "
"value can change over time. The `BranchFactor` attribute defines the "
"subdivision factor used for tree decomposition."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:450
msgid ""
"HyperTrees are defined from a bit array describing tree decomposition, level "
"by level. For each tree, the `Descriptor` dataset has one bit for each cell "
"in the tree, except for its deepest level: 0 if the cell is not refined, and "
"1 if it is. The descriptor does not describe its deepest level, because we "
"know that no cell is ever refined."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:452
msgid ""
"Each cell can be masked using an optional bit array `Mask`. A decomposed "
"(refined) cell cannot be masked. The `Descriptors` and `Mask` datasets are "
"packed bit arrays, stored as unsigned chars."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:455
msgid ""
"Each new piece is required to start writing descriptors and mask on a new "
"byte, even if the previous byte was not completely used, except if the "
"previous array has a size of 0. `DescriptorsSize` stores the size (in "
"**bits**) of the descriptors array for each piece."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:458
msgid ""
"`DepthPerTree` contains the depth of each tree listed in `TreeIds` the "
"current piece. The size of both arrays is `NumberOfTrees`, indexed at the "
"piece id."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:461
msgid ""
"`NumberOfCellsPerTreeDepth`'s size is the sum of `DepthPerTree`. For each "
"depth of each tree, it gives the information of the number of cells for this "
"depth. For a given piece, we store the size of this dataset as "
"`NumberOfDepths`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:465
msgid "The number of cells for the piece is stored as `NumberOfCells`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:467
msgid ""
"The size of the (optional) `Mask` dataset corresponds to the number of cells "
"divided by 8 (because of bit-packed storage), rounded to the next bigger "
"integer value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:470
msgid ""
"For HyperTreeGrids, edges cannot store information. This means there can be "
"a `CellData` group containing cell fields, but no `PointData`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:473
msgid ""
"Optionally, `InterfaceNormalsName` and `InterfaceInterceptsName` root "
"attributes can be set to existing cell array names to define HyperTreeGrid "
"interfaces, used for interpolation at render time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:476
msgid ""
"For temporal HyperTreeGrids, the \"Steps\" group contains read offsets into "
"the `DepthPerTree`, `NumberOfCellsPerTreeDepth`, `TreeIds`, `Mask` "
"`Descriptors` and coordinate datasets for each timestep."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:479
msgid ""
"If some values do not change over time (for example coordinates), you can "
"set the offset to the same value as the previous timestep (O),and store data "
"only once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:482
msgid ""
"Note that for `Mask` and `Descriptors`, the offset is in **bytes** (unlike "
"`DescriptorSize` which is in bits), because each new piece starts on a new "
"byte, except if it does not contain any value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:545
msgid ""
"<div align=\"center\">\n"
"Figure 5. - HyperTreeGrid VTKHDF File Format\n"
"</div>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:549
msgid "PartitionedDataSetCollection and MultiBlockDataSet"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:551
msgid ""
"VTKHDF supports composite types, made of multiple datasets of simple types, "
"organized as a tree. The format currently supports "
"vtkPartitionedDataSetCollection (PDC) and vtkMultiBlockDataSet (MB) "
"composite types, as shown in Figure 11. The `Type` attribute of the `VTKHDF` "
"group for them should be either `PartitionedDataSetCollection` or "
"`MultiBlockDataSet`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:555
msgid ""
"All simple (non composite) datasets are located in the root `VTKHDF` group, "
"with a unique block name. These blocks can have any simple `Type` specified "
"above, or be empty blocks when no `Type` is specified. These top-level data "
"blocks should not be composite themselves : they can only be simple or "
"partitioned (multi-piece) types. For temporal datasets, all blocks should "
"have the same number of time steps and time values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:560
msgid ""
"Then, dataset tree hierarchy is defined in the `Assembly` group, which is "
"also a direct child of the `VTKHDF` group. Sub-groups in the `Assembly` "
"group define the dataset(s) they contain using a [HDF5 symbolic link]"
"(https://davis.lbl.gov/Manuals/HDF5-1.8.7/UG/09_Groups."
"html#HardAndSymbolicLinks) to the top-level datasets. The name of the link "
"target in the assembly will be the actual name of the block when read. Any "
"group can have multiple children that are either links to datasets, or nodes "
"that define datasets deeper in the hierarchy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:565
msgid "**Track Creation Order**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:569
msgid ""
"VTKHDF group, the Assembly group and its children need to track creation "
"order so we always read them ordered properly. For this, you need to set H5G "
"properties `H5P_CRT_ORDER_TRACKED` and `H5P_CRT_ORDER_INDEXED` on each group "
"when writing the Assembly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:573
msgid ""
"While both MB and PDC share a common structure, there is still a slight "
"distinction in the format between them. This is caused by an internal "
"storage different between MB and PDC; both data classes are not 100% "
"compatible with each other."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:576
msgid ""
"Multiblock define their structure recursively, nesting multiblocks inside of "
"other multiblocks to achieve multi-level nesting. PDC store their leaf "
"datasets in an indexed list, and their structure in a separate object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:578
msgid "The dataset list associates an integer index to a dataset object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:579
msgid ""
"The `vtkDataAssembly`object defines structure using a tree of nodes. Each "
"node of the tree can be associated to one or more datasets from the indexed "
"dataset list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:581
msgid ""
"In practice, for PDC in VTKHDF, a group in the `Assembly` group is either:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:582
msgid "Not a softlink, and represents a node in the vtkDataAssembly tree."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:583
msgid ""
"A softlink that points to a non-composite block group in the `VTKHDF` group. "
"It represents the association of its parent node in the tree structure with "
"an indexed dataset in the flat list, similar to what the function "
"`AddDataSetIndex` does in `vtkDataAssembly`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:585
msgid ""
"This way, a single dataset can be used multiple times in the assembly "
"without any additional storage cost. Top-level datasets need to set an "
"`Index` attribute to specify their index in the PDC flat dataset array. This "
"index needs to be globally unique."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:588
msgid ""
"On the other hand, MB structures don't need an index for their leaf "
"datasets, and an assembly node that is not a softlink represents a nested "
"`vtkMultiBlockDataSet`. A softlink in the assembly represents a dataset "
"nested in its parent `vtkMultiBlockDataSet`. Again, this MB format can save "
"space when a block is referenced multiple times."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:627
msgid ""
"<div align=\"center\">\n"
"Figure 6. - PartitionedDataSetCollection/MultiBlockDataset VTKHDF File "
"Format\n"
"</div>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:632
msgid "Temporal Data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:634
msgid ""
"The generic format for all `VTKHDF` temporal data is shown in Figure 7. The "
"general idea is to take the static formats described above and use them as a "
"base to append all the time dependent data. As such, a file holding static "
"data has a very similar structure to a file holding dynamic data. For a non-"
"composite dataset, an additional `Steps` subgroup is added to the `VTKHDF` "
"main group holding offset information for each of the time steps as well as "
"the time values. The choice to include offset information as HDF5 datasets "
"was made to reduce the quantity of meta-data in the file to improve "
"performance. This `Steps` group has one integer like attribute `NSteps` "
"indicating the number of steps in the temporal dataset."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:644
msgid "The `Steps` group is structured as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:645
msgid ""
"`Values` [dim = (NSteps)]: each entry indicates the time value for the "
"associated time step."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:647
msgid ""
"`PartOffsets` [dims = (NSteps)]: each entry indicates at which part offset "
"to start reading the associated time step (relevant for `Unstructured Grid`s "
"and `Poly Data`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:650
msgid ""
"`NumberOfParts` [dims = (NSteps)]: each entry indicates how many parts the "
"associated time step has (relevant for `Unstructured Grid`s and `Poly "
"Data`). This information is optional if there is a constant number of parts "
"per time steps and the length of `VTKHDF/NumberOfPoints` is equal to "
"`NumberOfPartsPerTimeStep x NSteps`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:654
msgid ""
"`PointOffsets` [dims = (NSteps)]: each entry indicates where in the `VTKHDF/"
"Points` data set to start reading point coordinates for the associated time "
"step (relevant for `Unstructured Grid` and `Poly Data`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:657
msgid ""
"`CellOffsets` [dims = (NSteps, NTopologies)]: each entry indicates by how "
"many cells to offset reading into the connectivity offset structures for the "
"associated time step (relevant for `Unstructured Grid` and `Poly Data`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:660
#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:666
msgid ""
"`Unstructured Grid`s only have one set of connectivity data and NTopologies "
"= 1."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:661
#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:667
msgid ""
"`Poly Data`, however, have `Vertices`,`Lines`, `Polygons` and `Strips` in "
"that order and therefore NTopologies = 4."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:663
msgid ""
"`ConnectivityIdOffsets` [dims = (NSteps, NTopologies)]: each entry indicates "
"by how many values to offset reading into the connectivity indexing "
"structures for the associated time step (relevant for `Unstructured Grid` "
"and `Poly Data`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:669
msgid ""
"`{Point,Cell,Field}DataOffsets/{ArrayName}` [dims = (NSteps)]: each entry "
"indicates by how many values to offset reading into the given array for the "
"associated time step. In the absence of a data set, the appropriate geometry "
"offsetting for the time step is used in its place."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:673
msgid ""
"`FieldDataSizes/{ArrayName}` [dims = (NSteps, 2)]: each entry indicates the "
"field data component and tuple size. In the absence of a data set, the "
"maximum number of components and one tuple per step are considered."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:723
msgid ""
"<div align=\"center\">\n"
"Figure 7. - Temporal Data VTKHDF File Format\n"
"</div>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:728
msgid ""
"`VTKHDF` group should look exactly as it does for no time steps except that "
"the main dimensions of the datasets incorporate the potentially evolving "
"time data as well. Individual time steps can be accessed in these flattened "
"arrays through the offset information in the `Steps` group by slicing the "
"data. Offset value can be repeated for static data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:731
msgid ""
"Writing incrementally to `VTKHDF` temporal datasets is relatively "
"straightforward using the appending functionality of `HDF5` chunked data "
"sets ([Chunking in HDF5](https://davis.lbl.gov/Manuals/HDF5-1.8.7/Advanced/"
"Chunking/index.html))."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:735
msgid "Temporal UnstructuredGrid and PolyData"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:737
msgid ""
"Adding data for a new time step works the same way as adding a data for a "
"new partition: data is added at the end of existing datasets, and a new "
"value is added to \"count\" elements for `NumberOfPoints`, `NumberOfCells` "
"and `NumberOfConnectivityIds`. For instance, given an object of 2 partitions "
"changing over 10 time steps, `NumberOf...` datasets would contain 20 total "
"values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:742
msgid "Temporal UnstructuredGrid with polyhedrons"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:744
msgid ""
"Polyhedrons define face cells and a `PolyhedronToFaces` field that links "
"faces to polyhedrons. When writing a temporal UnstructuredGrid that uses "
"polyhedrons, you need to define additional fields `Steps/"
"FaceConnectivityOffsets`, `Steps/FaceOffsetsOffsets` and `Steps/"
"PolyhedronToFaceIdOffsets`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:748
msgid ""
"These fields dictate, for each time step, what the read offset should be "
"respectively for `FaceConnectivity`, `FaceOffsets` and `PolyhedronToFaceIds`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:751
msgid "Temporal ImageData"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:753
msgid ""
"A particularity of temporal `Image Data` in the format is that the reader "
"expects an additional prepended dimension considering the time to be the "
"first dimension in the multidimensional arrays. As such, arrays described in "
"temporal `Image Data` should have dimensions ordered as `(time, z, y, x)`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:758
msgid "Temporal OverlappingAMR"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:760
msgid ""
"Currently only `AMRBox` and `Point/Cell/Field data` can be temporal, not the "
"`Spacing`. Due to the structure of the OverlappingAMR format, the format "
"specify an intermediary group between the `Steps` group and the `Point/Cell/"
"FieldDataOffsets` group named `LevelX` for each level where `X` is the "
"number of level. These `Level` groups will also contain 2 other datasets to "
"retrieve the `AMRBox`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:765
msgid ""
"`AMRBoxOffsets` : each entry indicates by how many AMR box to offset reading "
"into the `AMRBox`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:766
msgid ""
"`NumberOfAMRBoxes` : the number of boxes contained in the `AMRBox` for each "
"timestep."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:817
msgid ""
"<div align=\"center\">\n"
"Figure 8. - Temporal OverlappingAMR VTKHDF File Format\n"
"</div>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:821
msgid "Temporal composite dataset"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:823
msgid ""
"For temporal composite datasets, there is no top-level `/VTKHDF/Steps` "
"group, but each block defines its time and offset values in its own `Steps` "
"group, in `/VTKHDF/<BlockName>/Steps` (see Figure 9). Each block should have "
"the same number of time steps, and the same time values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:862
msgid ""
"<div align=\"center\">\n"
"Figure 9. - Temporal Composite DataSet VTKHDF File Format\n"
"</div>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:866
msgid "**Steps defined in multiple Block**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:869
msgid ""
"Having different value in the attribute `NSteps` of the group `Step` between "
"Block is not supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:873
msgid ""
"Not all blocks need to define a `Steps` group, if a block doesn't have it, a "
"temporal data array will be considered to be a \"partial\" array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:876
msgid "Limitations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../vtk_file_formats/vtkhdf_file_format/vtkhdf_specifications.md:878
msgid ""
"Unlike XML formats, VTKHDF does not support field names containing `/` and `."
"` characters, because of a limitation in the HDF5 format specification."
msgstr ""
